The Jensen-Shannon distance is the square root of the Jensen-Shannon divergence73. The range of this metric ranges between [0, 1] where 0 implies the distributions are similar. We prefer JS divergence over KL divergence since it is a symmetric measure. If P and Q are two probability vectors, then the JS distance JS(P, Q) is given by5JS(P,Q)=KL(P∣∣M)+KL(Q∣∣M)2,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm{JS}}(P,Q)=\sqrt{\frac{{\rm{KL}}(P| | M)+{\rm{KL}}(Q| | M)}{2}},$$\end{document}where M is the pointwise mean of P and Q and KL is the Kullback-Leibler divergence. To supplement our study, we use Hellinger distance as a second metric to quantify the similarity between two probability distributions. Hellinger distance is also a symmetric measure. Its range of values is [0, 1] with 0 encoding that the distributions are similar. The Hellinger distance of two probability vectors P and Q is denoted by H(P, Q) and defined as6H(P,Q)=12∑i=1kpi−qi2,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\rm{H}}(P,Q)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\sqrt{\mathop{\sum }\limits_{i=1}^{k}{\left(\sqrt{{p}_{i}}-\sqrt{{q}_{i}}\right)}^{2}},$$\end{document}where k is the length of the vectors, and pi, qi are the ith elements of the vectors P and Q, respectively.

